We did get the updated framework agreement between the executive and providers to continue to go through and go forward on this conversation that has been convened, to really make sure we are working together as a council as the broader community and Mayor, to start making material progress on getting outreach and services to folks who really, really need it right now, especially now that we are very clearly on the doorstep of winter.

We have a variety of proposals that have come forward.

And for the city to be in a coordinating and service providing role that is enhancing the mission of those providers.
This is a good start to finish out 2020.
It is good that we have been able to convene a conversation where we are moving up closer to a consensus in this area.
And we will continue to talk about what the model for 2021 is going to look like throughout the fall budget session.
What we cannot wait any longer, based on the urgency and need to really start deploying these resources, that is evident in all the districts of the city, that sense of urgency.

I intend to vote no on this bill because what actually does is shrink the scale of the proviso passed by the Council to stop the encampment Removals or as homeless activists have said, stop the Sweeps.
One third shrinks the scale by almost a third, to $2 million.

The proviso basically said the Mayor could only use the funds allocated to the so-called navigation team which does the Sweeps of homeless people, that could use those funds to do genuine outreach of homeless services instead.
Councilmember Lewis says everyone has been working on good faith.
I think that is true of the workers at reach and the employees of the human services Department.
But I don't believe that is true of the Mayor's office which is actually been an obstacle to getting any kind of change away from Removals of homeless Encampments and homeless human beings.
Everything else has been discussed as part of this bill suggest principles and agreed framework of service providers.
All of which of course is moving in a good direction but could've happened anyway and do not require this legislation.
This is precisely for shrinking the scale of the proviso.

What the Council is really voting on is whether or not to shrink the Sweeps . The only reason it's being discussed is because Mayor Durkan refused to follow the proviso . As of last Friday my office checked with city council staff and it is still not being acted on.
The proviso is not being acted on.
It is true because the Mayor vetoed the budget it did not legally take effect until last Thursday.
But there is nothing stopping the Mayor from voluntarily following the proviso earlier.
So I don't actually take these claims about a sense of urgency at face value.
The only reason Mayor Durkan chose not to follow the proviso is because she was confident the city council would give her retroactive permission to do so in this bill will do just that.
I will say also I am really taken aback that this retroactive permission is being considered before the Mayor takes any material steps to follow the proviso.
Perhaps it would be different if it were December and the Mayor had dutifully followed the legal requirements and was then after that asking for retroactive permission for her slow start.
This bill gives her permission for being late before she even Beins.
What is to prevent her from delaying a couple of months and then bringing another bill trying to get permission for the next delay?
Don't know that is not going to happen.
The Sweeps of homeless Encampments are cruel, inhumane and ineffective.
People are removed again and again and again sometimes from the same location but there is nowhere for them to go.
There are no alternatives.

There have been well over 1000 Sweeps and they are clearly not working and they are wasting millions of dollars, forcing people to move, losing their belongings and becoming more and more desperate . The Mayor should've stopped sweeping people years ago.
It is not possible for my office to support a bill to retroactively give the Mayor permission for dealing after the proviso has been passed.

I understand were folks who have some skepticism about this legislation are coming from based on the history of the old navigation team . a lot of the issues we have seen over the last three years around collaboration between the city and provider community which I think we can all agree has not in and of itself been able to solve our homelessness crisis.

And we see every day thousands of our neighbors living without basic necessities, without basic hygiene facilities and as Councilmember Lewis often says, in this bill is not going to solve all of that neatly.
But it is a step in the right direction to start this collaborative process of working through this with all of the principal operator in this area.
I would note that while we are revising the pro Visa from the summer, only $245,000 is going back to the human services Department.

$245,000, the last two months of the year and over $2 million is going to be released to service providers also based on revisions of what that many can be going to based on collaboration and conversation providers and what they really need based on what they are experiencing now in the field.
That includes more money for behavioral mental health services.
Flexible financial assistance.
Case management to expand existing case management contracts.
Housing navigation.

As well as technology needs for service providers so, what we have a lot of work to do and this one thing is not going to solve all of it, this is an important step forward and a continuing to come together to really bring action and respond to what we are seeing in the city.

There were folks in public comments who were staying there in frustration about the city having been bogged down and really important visitors about the future direction of what are homeless's response is going to look like.

Is the first step to all of us realizing our common interest in this and moving forward in a way that can hopefully finally bridge the divide and get people the really critical resources they need and that this Council has appropriated money to address.
